segments.text: classes getting up going to class drill and so forth when did well it started about 6 30 in the morning when you're waking up by the whistle jock blow in the whistle and get up and get dressed and go out march to chow and we did that we marched chow morning noon at night when i was here and uh go chow are you gonna come back
Take care of your room because you're always subject to being inspected, which was a good habit to get into.
All those things are habits that you get into in life.
And if you're messy and sloppy with your room, you tend to be that way.
You took care of that and you went on to class.
Class, everybody walked to class.
It was always, sometimes it was difficult to get from one spot to the other on this campus because it is a large campus.
I recall having a PE class at G. Riley White and then the next hour having a chemistry class and the chemistry class was almost on the other side of the campus.
And it was always difficult to get from there to the other point.
But it was a pleasant deal.
You knew so many of the students.
spoke to your students, fellow students.
At one time, we started having a lot of civilian students who were transfers in or who did not get into the Corps or whatever.
But you still got to know them.
And by you, not as well as you did with the kids in the Corps, but you still certainly became more acquainted than I think they're existing now because primary science.
And we had some great professors.
I say to folks, they don't have professors.
They had nicknames.
Professors had nicknames.
Please, please, we want those nicknames.
Oh, we had.
And if you know why they were nicknamed what they were.
Oh, yes.
Well, we had Ivy League Taylor, because he graduated from the Ivy League.
He was always tagging the Ivy Leagues.
And he always dressed like, he always had the tweed jacket with the elbow patches and the pipe and the whole bit, you know, the.
He looked the part, he acted the part, but he was a good professor.
We had Blue Book Benton, because you used to take these poli-sci and history exams in the Blue Books.
Well, you better take more than one if you take his exams.
We had a guy named C.S.
Hampton.
That was the initials for you.
He was a soil science professor, and I will forget the first time I had one of his quizzes.

comes in and delivers the quizzes to the class and it's in a little box and pulls the papers out of the box and on top of the box are all these feathers and he goes and blows the feathers off and says just want you all to know that I do earn my nickname and passed out the quiz and I'll tell you he earned his nickname it was a chicken quiz it was tough it was a tough course we had uh
Screamin' Al Nelson.
He would get excited about the deal.
He just didn't scream it up, his voice.
His antics were always on campus.
Everybody talked about it.
Others, you know, they were characters.
Math?
Math?
I don't...
I had a farm.
So you didn't have...
square root or cube root?
No, I didn't have a square root or cube root.
Chemistry?
Biology?
Chemistry?
Oh, I had Dr. Sweet.
We called him Dr. Tweet.
Dr. Tweet had a very significant hearing deficiency.
So as a result of the effect of his speech, and his name was Sweet, but he pronounced it Tweet.
And in a large lecture class, like biology was,
I remember one day during class, he was talking about RNA and DNA and all sorts of stuff that was rolling around my mind and I wasn't quite grasping.

Raised my hand, he asked me if there was any question, raised my hand and I said, Dr. Sweet, would you, and I went into my question and he says, when I got through with it, he looked at me and he says, yes, that's right, and went right on with the lecture.
I said, why bother, you know.
We had, uh,
Dr. Smith, the geology department, that if you went to sleep in his class, you'd get ready because a racer or a piece of chalk was coming your way.
And he had a pretty good arm, too.
There were just a lot of professors that, I was calling Pat Freddie Smith, so there was Fred Smith, Pat Freddie.
But they really had a lot of characters, but they were professors.
that I felt really didn't care about the students.
And I never found a professor yet that if I was having some difficulty with the subject that I went to, they wouldn't do everything they could to be helpful.
What about advisors, staff members that you remember?
Oh, some of the folks that were around then are still around.
I remember that I was
I was head yell leader my senior year, and Malin Southern was the faculty advisor for that.
What was his nickname?
The Slink.
Used to call him the Slink because he'd go slinking around the dorms trying to catch boats, you know, doing improper things.
The Wedge?
I don't remember that.
Maybe that was different, because the simplest of two would own the mail.
That was what happened.
It was the Wedge.
All right.
Were there other key corps staff people?
Oh, yes.
Of course, you had the folks in the trigon, but I changed out from town to town.
I remember one guy in particular who was Captain Salamosi.
They called him the White Russian.
And he was just a very intense sort of a fellow, a little bit in general, Salamosi.
And a great guy.
But I believe he was the son
Russian immigrants, as a matter of fact, is why I call him quite Russian.
Great guy, really sharp guy, but he was an intense officer.
You started a while ago.
Describe Mr. Rutter and your impression and your evaluation of him.

General Rutter, when you were an underclassman and your only involvement was maybe another graduation or commissioning ceremony and having President Rutter give his speech, he was not a great speech giver.
He could put you to sleep pretty quickly in the way he gave a speech.
And so you kind of had an impression sometimes of an old, doddery old guy, you know, sort of a deal.
But when you got to be a student leader, when you came into contact with the president, your opinion changed very quickly.
My impression was the first time I met with him,
I was on staff my junior year, and I was a class officer, things of this nature.
It may have been, I was an RV, too.
I don't know what it was, but anyway, he had me.
And we started talking about the university and its role and our function as leaders and things of this nature.
It wasn't one of these written speeches.
This was off-the-cuff General Ruddard talking to the troops.
And he got a different impression.
And later on, I was head-yellied at my senior year.
And I was listening to some other things.
And so you ended up with a lot more personal meetings then.
And you've got to have the point.
If you were to open your mouth and say something at the meeting with the general, you better know what you're talking about and be able to back it up, because he did.
And he'd jam your little thing right up your, down your throat if you didn't have your stuff together.
And I did have, with my respect, just
went up many, many fold of General Rutter.
There is one story of General Rutter, though, that not many people get chewed up and spit out like I did one day by General Rutter.
My senior year, as I said, I was head Yeliger, and we had a young man who was selected as a junior Yeliger who was a civilian student.
He's now a candidate for governor, Gary Marlowe.
And General Rutter
called me into his office that spring before school was let out.
And he said, Bill, you're going to be a Yale leader.
You've got this young man, a civilian student.
And that's the most visible position there is on this campus.
And he said, I expect you to make sure that nothing happens that would bring disgrace upon this university, upon Yale leaders, you, me.
Anybody in any shape or fashion, you understand that?
I said, yes sir, I sure do, General.
You got your words from the General.
You knew what they were, you know.
Well, Gary wore a belt to the first Yale practice that had the junior and senior from the Corps on it.
I didn't know what he had.
I didn't care, you know.
But some of the junior members took offense at that next Yale practice.
They had the freshman jump in and they took his belt off of him and the whole bit.
Anyway, I held the junior class afterwards and I chewed the rearing out and I was in front of the family who did all this stuff.
I remember it's 0600 the next morning, I get a call from Joe Buser, who was the general's aide.
And Joe says the general will see that 0700 is off, which was over in the systems building.
I said, yes, sir.
So I was over there.
And he was in his office, and I was outside waiting.
And the secretary just got there, and says, the general's over here.
He wants to see you.
And I walked in, and I stood at attention the whole time.
It was like I was a freshman on the walls of the court.
He walked one out on me, chewing at me.
You know, I did this, and you told me to do this.
And I'm, yes, sir, no, sir, no excuse.
I mean, boy, it was.
He ate on me for a little while there, and he said, Dismissed.
I said, Yes, sir.
I turned around, and I got out of there.
On the way out, the secretary said, Colonel McCoy wants to see you.
He was calling me.
So I go over to Colonel McCoy, and as I'm going in the door, Captain Salamosi said, I want to see you when he gets through.
So I go in, and he chews on me for a while, but he wasn't near as good a general as two of them.
And then Captain Salamosi says, If I spin it,
from about 7 o'clock to 11 o'clock that day getting chewed on by everybody by a chain of command.
What had you done wrong?
Oh, nothing.
I had failed to maintain control of the situation, and I was told in no uncertain terms that I was supposed to anticipate things like this, and I guess I should have.
I didn't think to inspect his uniform and see those things, but anyway, he got to keep his belt, and it never happened again, I'll assure you that.
And nothing came of the incident.
But my appreciation for the general just went up immediately.
From that point on, I was involved in other meetings with world leaders.
General Wilson Moore came to campus one time.
And I remember how the respect that he was held by people like that.
And my pride in my university, my pride in him as the president of the university just
just kept increasing.
And I sat down with Miss Rudder one time and told her how much you double, your appreciation grows as time goes on.
And told her how much I appreciate Virginia.
And she said, well, you're just not the first one who's told me that.
And I said, yes, ma'am, I didn't think so.
Describe some of the jokes, pranks, good bull that you may have known about, whether you participate in or not.
What were some of the good?
Oh.
There were a lot of things that happened that some people might consider strange or outrageous, but we considered kind of funny.
It was, I do recall one incident.
I had these friends I graduated with, those 13 guys, really were all innovative with the first bunch of characters, but great guys.
I do recall the first week when you were a senior, you were back on campus.
Well, you waited to wear those boots for a long time, and so you wear those boots wherever you go, you know, class and everything else.
And boots, by the way, are a pain to maintain, because you're always rubbing against something, and the polishing and stuff is a problem.
But I know one day, one of our classmates was coming back from class,
His name is Steve Beachy.
He's the director of Parks and Recreation at the City College Station.
He's the one that's put their program on the map out there.
He's done a great job.
But Beachy was coming back from class and one of my buddies had the fish jump Beachy.
They take his clothes off of him and they put him in a mattress cover and they drag him to a mud hole and they hang him from one of those trees in the mattress cover.
It's in the quad there, and they let him cure for about three or four hours until about 10 o'clock that night.
And he was a little irritated at that.
But Beachy's one of those type of guys that you just didn't mess with because he would get even.
And Judd McNeil was the guy that did it.
We called him Big Judd.
Judd was about six foot two.
He weighed about 270 pounds.
He wasn't fat.
He was just big.
I mean, his fingers were like twice the size of my fingers.
He was just a big man, like a big oak tree.
And every day that Beechy would see him, he would tell him, maybe not today, maybe tomorrow.
That it's going to happen.
He had him jump here because he knew something would happen.
So one day, McNeil's coming back from class, and his signature was not lit.
So Beechy had his freshman jump in, took every half a fish out of it, and held it down.
They stripped him, and they drove four iron stakes in the ground, and they stretched him out, and tied his hands and feet to these stakes.
And so he's just
naked there in front of God and everybody.
This is for women, really, we're on campus too much.
And so Beech says, okay, and he had the freshman get stuff.
So they have a freshman comes out and he has this jar of honey, he pours it all over him, you know, spreads it around a little bit.
And the other one had a sack and it was cracked corn.
So he throws this cracked corn all over him and stick him to that honey on his body and everything else.
And then Beech says, go get him.
So the freshman go in to Beech's room and he brings out three chickens.
that he had bought at the hatchery down here on Finnfeather, that he had starved in his closet for three days.
And they turned those chickens loose, and they were pecking at corn, and McNeil was just bouncing and jumping up and down.
Oh, let me go.
Get them off of me.
It was hilarious.
Of course, every time they'd peck you, they'd leave a red mark.
When we got through the beach, he suddenly says, McNeil, don't ever mess with me again.
I said, don't worry.
I won't.
There were other things that happened that were just, that were funny, that were hilarious.
But it was, I know another one that, another one of my friends, he ended up being CO of the outfit.
He was one of the parachute club.
He was the one whose father was the commander of the special forces.
And so he was going to go airborne and stuff and he was a sport jumper.
And he always kept his,
He was repacking his chute out there.
He just took it and just threw it in the bottom of his closet, and it was all loose and everything.
And he was also, he was a wildlife science major, so at one point in time, he had to collect all these snakes.
And he had them in his big mayonnaise jar in his room.
It was three snakes, and there was two of them were poisonous.
One of them was not.
I don't recall what the word was.
But Dick Judd, again, told him, he said, I don't like snakes.
I don't want you to have these snakes in the dorm.
I want you to get rid of them.
He said, oh, Dick Judd, I got them in this jar.
They don't even bother you, et cetera.
He said, I don't want them.
Get them out.
He said, I'll keep it.
So McKean goes out on a date with a lady who had been his wife.
And they're on the first floor, I think, of Norma's house at one time.
And so McKean goes in with an empty mayonnaise jar and just holds it and just drops it.
And it crashes on the floor.
Picks up the jar of snakes and takes them and leaves with them.
And so we have a freshman waiting out in the senior parking lot for him.
when he gets back.
It's about 1.32 in the morning.
He says, he's coming in.
He's coming in the dorm.
So we all go out and sit out in chairs outside of his dorm.
And he couldn't see us, but you see in the dorm, in the window of the dorm.
And so he flips the light on.
He's tired.
He's sleeping.
He starts getting his clothes off.
He's down to his underwear.
He hasn't seen the broken jar yet.
And about the time he finally sees the jar,
He's just fixing into bed and sees a jar.
Boy, he jumps up on the bed.
And his boots hung in boot covers on the wall.
So he took his senior boots and he put them on, you know.
And he's walking around.
We got him a little stick or a ruler or something.
He's trying to see if he can find those snakes.
He can't find them.
So he goes in the closet and there's his chute.
You know, he's parachuted.
So he pulls one of them.
He shut eggs, parachuted, pulls and shakes.
Can't find any snakes anywhere.
So he goes and wakes up the freshman next door to,
wake up everybody in the dorm and tell me, boy, the snake's loose.
By the time Neil walks in and says, I got you, snakes, but next time I am turning loose in your bed.
The snakes left the dorm.
But that's just some of the things.
There are other things.
Yeah, that is good bull.
What was the difference for you in being a sophomore and being a freshman?
There is a marked difference.
When you're a freshman, what you find out really is that once you've learned
The people out there were there to really try to improve you and to mold you as a group together.
And you start doing that, and you don't know how the game is played.
Then you realize they're just playing with you.
And you end up kind of liking it, and you realize they like you, and you're liking them, on top of the other side.
But a sophomore kind of stands at the side and doesn't participate in anything.
Nobody likes a sophomore, including sophomores.
And that was a big difference that year.
And what I did observe as my freshman year, and those sophomores that, as a freshman, couldn't kind of have been more than that.
And I said, which persons do I respect that are sophomores, and which ones do I think do a good job?

And I really, that was one of the benefits that you get to see is who could deal with you in an effective way and in a way you respect when they're dealing with you like sophomores have to do, and those that don't.
And I adapted that, hopefully.
I think he knows that I respect and admire him.
And it gave you, it really helped me.
And then I did my job my sophomore year, and I made grades.
The sophomore's job basically was to do his job and kind of stay out of the way.
And that's what I did, and I ended up making grades that semester.
And that's, you position yourself your freshman year to really understand what it's all about, and to make certain decisions in your life, realizations about yourself that you can make it.
You can make it academic, but it depends.
Your sophomore year is to position yourself for your career at the college.
I don't care where it is.
Your sophomore year really is the year that sets you up for what you're going to do junior and senior year.
What was your normal practice in terms of class attendance, class participation, preparation, and so forth?
Well, my normal deal was, and I will tell you that one of the other benefits I got was I did not really have study skills and habits.
I had made good grades my entire life.
I had scored well on the test.
I had a scholarship.
I graduated with honors from high school.
I was always a, quote, good student and one of the, quote, smart kids and things of this nature.
I got in here and realized there are a bunch of times smart folks are a lot smarter than I was, and it was not easy to do.
As a matter of fact, I recall the first test I ever took was this math course.
I made a 45-hour exam.
And the thoughts that went through my mind were, I'm going to flunk this course.
I'm going to flunk out of school.
I'm going to lose my scholarship.
I'm going to embarrass my family and friends.
I'm going to get drafted with the Army.
I'm going to get sent to Vietnam and get killed.
I mean, that was my thought process.
And after that, I wrote, I've got to buckle down, and I've got to study.
And I did.
And I made not good grades that first semester, but better than most of my classmates.
in the outfit.
And then by my sophomore year, my second semester, I learned a little more about what you had to do and had to do.
And my sophomore year, I really, I bucked that and I made grades.
I de-essed and things of that nature.
Really, really made grades, set myself up to get on down the line, so to speak.
And that was also the time I kind of made some career decisions about what I wanted to do.
I go to law school and things of that nature.
So that was a big difference for me.
But it was one of those years that was a successful year, but it was not a fun year.
I didn't enjoy my sophomore year much as I did my freshman year, believe it or not, and my later years.
And I think it's kind of typical.
Describe the role of the MSC and its activities for students in your undergraduate years.
The MSC was one of those places that was kind
It was like home base.
It was a safe spot.
You could go and sit out over there with your friends and have coffee and donut and relax.
And it was there for everybody.
It was the family room of the campus, so to speak.
And the social life and all those kind of things at the campus kind of radiated from all that.
And it was very much an important aspect of the student life here.
I got involved in it.
My junior and senior year, I was town hall staff.
Well, I got into it and enjoyed that tremendously.
My roommate, my junior year, was president of MSC, our senior year, who was in the Sims yesterday.
And got to be with him, because he was a lot more involved in MSC than I was, obviously, but worked with him.
stuff there.
It was very much an integral part of a student's life and it still is.
And it is that way that a lot of folks really get to get involved in something on their campus.
Through the MSC did you ever come in contact with some famous visitors?
Oh sure.
Let's see, I do remember General Westmoreland came while I was here.
Oh, gosh, I can't remember.
There was a former British prime minister, General McNamara, whose defense secretary came.
There were...
Were you part of SCONA?
No, I was not.
I wasn't part of SCONA.
Describe Wayne Stark.
The gentleman.
a tall, stately gentleman.
And ever since the war, he was a person of great character.
But I had a refinement to him that you didn't see in a lot of other folks.
And I think Jay Winstar probably was responsible for opening so many doors for so many former students.
That's really unbelievable.
Like I said, I didn't have any problem with him at the moment, but I was always just very much impressed with and very, very much in confidence in all of Mr. Stark.
He would stir the pot a little bit, but he let the kids primarily do, he might kind of direct them, kind of push them a little bit, but whatever happened, they did.
He changed a lot of lines.
What role did Guy and Hall play in that time?
Well, it was the first moment I had with us where our freshman was taking over to see the movie Never Been Licked, which I thought was a pretty bad movie then.
It still is, but it was the only one about A&M.
But I saw that, and of course, that was where all the other
A lot of other performances took place, theater performances and entertainment things, until finally got to the point where they started having these concerts that you had to go to right away.
It was the three of them.
It was a classy building, too, I thought.
I enjoyed it.
Do you remember any religious activities on campus?
No, not really.
I don't remember much religious activities on campus.
I do know that we were always encouraged
Of course, I came from a very strict religious upbringing, East Texas Baptist family.
And most of the kids had the same kind of background.
And we were encouraged by the upper class, and I think the administration, too, to get involved with religious activities in the community.
And I didn't have a car, so I always walked to Northgate to church over there.

I ended up going quite a bit to St. Mary's Catholic Church because three of my good friends were Catholic boys, and they were a lot more punctual about their going to religious services than some of the Protestant boys were, so I went with them quite a bit to church.
But we did do it on a regular basis.
Were there any Jewish?
Do you remember any Jewish students?
Not very many.
I do remember some.
They were not a large number at all.
How were they treated?
Just like everybody else.
You know, the thing is, I tell folks, when I came down here, this thing about the content of your character and your ability, that was true.
The first person to ever graduate from A&M in the Corps of Cadets was a black boy.
He was one of my classmates.
My Corps commander
was Hector Gutierrez, a little Mexican boy from Laredo.
Everybody was accepted for their character and their ability.
All those little things were kind of taken away.
And that was one of those marvelous things I thought about, that experience.
This black corps graduate, how was he treated?
Like all the rest of the freshman, not very well.
But none of us were treated well.
And did anybody single him out?
Uh, you know, uh, maybe so.
I didn't, I wasn't in the same outfit, but I didn't notice it, uh, if it was.
And his name is Bill Mayholmes.
He's a lawyer up in Dallas.
Bill was from East Texas like I was.
He was from Lindale, Texas.
He'd never gone to school with a white person.
I'd never gone to school with a black person because those were days of segregation in this state.
And we came and we both, uh, succeeded at A&M.
based on our ability, and that was it.
Bill, as a matter of fact, I do recall one of the reunions, Bill came to the reunion with his wife, who was a wife he met later after college and stuff.
And I was sitting there just kind of visiting with her, and of course, everybody coming up, you know, and I said, Bill, how you doing?
She says, you know, we were sitting there,
You know, Bill's liked by a lot of folks, or known by a lot of folks, because he's a lawyer in Dallas, he's involved in a lot of civic activities up there, a very respected person.
I said, you know, it's difficult.
He said, you guys, y'all really like Bill.
I said, yeah, because Bill's just one of the guys.
I mean, you've got to understand that.
And she did, you know, but there was a distinction between people, treatment of Bill here and Bill's treatment, say, in Dallas or something.
But that was exactly the way it was.
I thought there were a couple other black kids.
I know there were a couple others that they did not graduate, but they left.
And they may have had some treatment that was improper.
I mean, one guy named Thompson.
But Bill graduated, and you have to ask Bill if there was some discrimination.
And I'm sure there probably was.
But it wasn't
to the point where we recommend it.
That was with Fresh Fish Buddies, and I asked several friends that were in his outfit, and they never remarked back to me either.
